Accrual Accounting
Definition: Record money when it’s earned or owed, not when cash actually comes or goes.
Example:
You sell a product today but the customer pays next month → you record revenue today.
You get a bill today but pay next month → you record expense today.
Advantage: Shows the true financial performance of a business.
Used in: Most businesses, GAAP & IFRS standards require this for financial statements.

Cash Accounting
Definition: Record money only when cash changes hands.
Example:
Sell product today, customer pays next month → record revenue next month.
Get electricity bill today, pay next month → record expense next month.
Advantage: Simple and easy for small businesses.
Limitation: Doesn’t show true profit/loss if money is owed or pending.

Hybrid Accounting
Definition: A mix of cash and accrual methods.
Example:
Small businesses may use cash accounting for day-to-day, but accrual for bigger invoices or taxes.
Advantage: Flexible and simpler than full accrual for small businesses.
